<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="178" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,151,176]" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The following combination of characters distinguishes 
<taxonomicName box="[950,1156,151,176]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Xenisthmidae" genus="Gymnoxenisthmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[950,1156,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">Gymnoxenisthmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other xenisthmid genera: head pores absent; scales lacking; first dorsal fin with five spines; second dorsal-fin rays I,13; most segmented dorsal- and anal-fin rays branched; pelvic fin with a spine and five unbranched rays.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="178" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,151,717]" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,260,285]" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">Remarks.</emphasis>
The discovery of 
<taxonomicName authority="Gill &amp; Bogorodsky &amp; Mal, 2019" authorityName="Gill &amp; Bogorodsky &amp; Mal" authorityYear="2019" box="[529,873,260,285]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Xenisthmidae" genus="Gymnoxenisthmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="flavicinctus" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[529,873,260,285]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">Gymnoxenisthmus flavicinctus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[883,1021,260,285]" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
necessitates revision of the original diagnosis for the genus. Previously we listed the presence of branched pectoral-fin rays as a diagnostic character of the genus, but the new species has entirely unbranched pectoral-fin rays. Entirely unbranched pectoral-fin rays is one of several characters that we proposed as synapomorphies of a clade consisting of 
<taxonomicName authority="Springer (1983)" authorityName="Springer" authorityYear="1983" box="[1172,1431,367,392]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Xenisthmidae" genus="Tyson" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1172,1235,369,392]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">Tyson</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Springer, V. G." box="[1247,1431,367,392]" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" pagination="1 - 40" refId="ref3374" refString="Springer, V. G. (1983) Tyson belos, new genus and species of western Pacific fish (Gobiidae, Xenisthminae), with discussions of gobioid osteology and classification. Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology, 390, 1 - 40. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00810282.390" type="journal article" year="1983">Springer (1983)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Springer (1988)" authorityName="Springer" authorityYear="1988" box="[151,437,404,429]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Xenisthmidae" genus="Rotuma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,238,405,428]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">Rotuma</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Springer, V. G." box="[252,437,404,429]" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" pagination="530 - 539" refId="ref3431" refString="Springer, V. G. (1988) Rotuma lewisi, new genus and species of fish from the southwest Pacific (Gobioidei, Xenisthmidae). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 101, 530 - 539." type="journal article" year="1988">Springer (1988)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Schultz in Schultz et al. (1966)" authorityName="Schultz in Schultz" authorityYear="1966" box="[505,1099,404,429]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Xenisthmidae" genus="Allomicrodesmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[505,698,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">Allomicrodesmus</emphasis>
Schultz in 
<bibRefCitation author="Schultz, L. P. &amp; Woods, L. P. &amp; Lachner, E. A." box="[846,1099,404,429]" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" pagination="1 - 176" refId="ref3263" refString="Schultz, L. P., Woods, L. P. &amp; Lachner, E. A. (1966) Fishes of the Marshall and Marianas islands. Vol. 3. Families Kraemeriidae through Antennariidae. Bulletin of the United States National Museum, 202 (3), 1 - 176." type="journal article" year="1966">
Schultz 
<emphasis box="[944,1007,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">et al.</emphasis>
(1966)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. The new species lacks the remaining proposed synapomorphies of this clade (all segmented second dorsal-fin rays unbranched; all segmented anal-fin rays unbranched; ceratohyals represented by a single ossification). This distribution of derived characters suggests that the new species should be placed in its own genus as sister-group to the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="178">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Springer" authorityYear="1983" box="[1207,1272,513,536]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Xenisthmidae" genus="Tyson" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Tyson</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Springer" authorityYear="1988" box="[1317,1404,513,536]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Xenisthmidae" genus="Rotuma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Rotuma</taxonomicName>
+ 
<taxonomicName box="[151,344,548,573]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Xenisthmidae" genus="Allomicrodesmus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="178" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Allomicrodesmus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
clade. However, the general similarity in form and coloration suggests the two species are closely related. We are also reluctant to erect additional monotypic genera when the osteology of neither species has been adequately studied. We note, however, that synapomorphies linking the two species are lacking, and the possibility remains that the genus as recognised here is paraphyletic. Further testing must await the discovery of additional specimens for more detailed anatomical study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
